LONDON, March 11 (Reuters) - The London Metal Exchange (LME) defended its decision to suspend nickel trading and cancel deals earlier this week when prices doubled within hours, saying the market had become disorderly, with prices not reflecting the physical market. "We recognise the frustration of some market participants regarding the decision to suspend nickel trading and to cancel Tuesday early-morning trades," it said in a statement on Friday. (This story corrects to change day to Friday) Our Standards: The Thomson Reuters Trust Principles.